          "body": "Saul's response in 26:21 is the most theologically loaded of his three confessions in 1 Samuel (see also 15:24-25 and 15:30). He acknowledges sin (chata), names his own folly (sakhal), and confesses serious error (shagah). He calls David 'my son.' He blesses him (26:25). On its face it is a complete repentance. Yet the narrative refuses to ratify it. David does not return. He sends a young man to retrieve the spear (26:22) rather than going himself — the physical distance between them is maintained. And the chapter's final verse places the two men firmly back in their respective orbits: 'David went on his way, and Saul returned to his place' (26:25). Saul's words are not matched by movement. The chapter does not say he disbanded his army, called off the pursuit, or restored David to court. By 28:3 Saul is in desperate straits at Endor, having lost access to God entirely. The chapter's final portrait of Saul is of a man whose confession came too late and went too shallow — words without the turning that would have made them real."
